Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Lukas Peterson¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Prosper Loan Data (prosperloanData.csv) represents personal loans requested through Prosper's peer to peer loan servicing network. Each row represents a loan with information on the listing request, loan details, and borrower's credit worthiness.

Cleaning Notes:

  • ProsperRating has 29084 missing values
  • EstimatedReturn has 29084 missing values (no solution, proceed to visualize while noting missing values for loans before July 2009)
  • Credit Scores are missing on 591 loans.
  • ProsperRating and ListingCategory column names contain additional info (Alpha) and (numeric)
  • ListingCategory values not descriptive
  • ProsperRating will need to be combined with CreditGrade to fill missing data from before July 2009.
  • Create CreditScoreAvg metric as an average of lower and upper Credit Score ranges

Define: CreditScoreRangeLower, CreditScoreRangeUpper¶

Drop rows without Credit Scores. Create a column CreditScoreAvg as a numeric average of the two CreditScoreRange variables.

Code¶

In [12]:
# Drop nulls
df.dropna(subset=['CreditScoreRangeLower', 'CreditScoreRangeUpper'], inplace=True)
In [13]:
# Create CreditScoreAvg
df['CreditScoreAvg'] = (df['CreditScoreRangeLower'] + df['CreditScoreRangeUpper'])/2

Define: ProsperRating, CreditGrade¶

Rename ProsperRating by dropping the (Alpha) suffix. Create a new column CombinedRating that iterates through the dataframe, selecting ProsperRating data if present, and CreditGrade data otherwise.

Code¶

In [15]:
# Rename column ProsperRating (keeping the alpha character rating)
df.rename(columns={'ProsperRating (Alpha)':'ProsperRating'}, inplace=True)
In [16]:
# Created CombinedRating column for CreditGrade and ProsperRating
ratings = []
rating_alpha = ['AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'HR']
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    if row['ProsperRating'] in rating_alpha:
        ratings.append(row['ProsperRating'])
    else:
        ratings.append(row['CreditGrade'])

df['CombinedRating'] = pd.Series(ratings)

Post Wrangling Notes¶

Data Structure¶

The dataset is 113937 rows, by 81 columns, representing loans from Nov 2005 to Mar 2014.

The data types are: bool(3), datetime64[ns](3), float64(50), int64(11), object(14)

Main feature of interest (Research Question)¶

What loan or borrower characteristics contribute to unfavorable loan outcomes (LoanStatus: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Defaulted, PastDue)

Data set features to support investigation¶

We will look at relationships between LoanStatus and BorrowerRate, EstimatedReturn, ProsperRating, ProsperScore, ListingCategory, LoanOriginalAmount, LoanOriginationDate, CreditScoreAvg, and Term. We will also dig into some of the relationships between independent variables

Univariate Exploration¶

Examine each variable's distribution and frequencies

LoanStatus¶

Frequencies of LoanStatus variable through:

  • original column categories
  • consolidated categories (Complete, Current, Defaulted, Chargedoff, PastDue, FinalPaymentInProgress, Cancelled)
  • Favorable vs Unfavorable outcomes {Favorable: Complete, Current, FinalPaymentInProgress}, {Unfavorable: Chargedoff, PastDue, Cancelled}

In [23]:
# Create a new variable for LoanStatus_cat that consolidates the categories into
# Complete, Current, Defaulted, Chargedoff, PastDue, FinalPaymentInProgress, Cancelled
LoanStatus_cat = []
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    if 'Past Due' in row['LoanStatus']:
        LoanStatus_cat.append('PastDue')
    else:
        LoanStatus_cat.append(row['LoanStatus'])

df['LoanStatus_cat'] = pd.Series(LoanStatus_cat)
In [24]:
# Frequency of LoanStatus consolidated categories
status_order = df['LoanStatus_cat'].value_counts().index
sb.countplot(data = df, y = 'LoanStatus_cat', color = base_color, order=status_order);
In [25]:
# Create a new binary good standing loan variable, LoanStatus_good that consolidates categories into
# Favorable and Unfavorable outcomes; T, F
LoanStatus_good = []
favorable = ['Completed', 'Current', 'FinalPaymentInProgress']
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    if row['LoanStatus'] in favorable:
        LoanStatus_good.append('T')
    else:
        LoanStatus_good.append('F')

df['LoanStatus_good'] = pd.Series(LoanStatus_good)
In [26]:
# Frequency of LoanStatus consolidated into favorable, unfavorable
sb.countplot(data = df, y = 'LoanStatus_good', color=base_color);

Most of the loans are Current or Complete. Unfavorable loan outcomes are far less common (PastDue, Canceled, Chargedoff). In the next section I will compare the unfavorable outcomes to several other variables to see if there are clear relationships.

Distribution of LoanStatus Notes:¶

Loan Status is our variable of most interest. We will look at correlations between variables that may suggest a loan will be in an unfavorable status (PastDue, Cancelled, Chargedoff). Most of the loans are in good standing. I created two new LoanStatus variables; LoanStatus_cat (Consolidates all PastDue categories) and LoanStatus_good (Consolidates all categories into good standing loan (T, Favorable) or not in good standing (F, Unfavorable).

Independent feature distributions of interest¶

Interesting/Unusual distributions:

  • BorrowerRate has an unusual spike at 3.2%
  • ProsperScore looks normally distributed, may be by choice of the firm
  • LoanOriginalAmount has several spikes at $5000 increments.
  • LoanOriginationDate has large decline during 2008 Financial Crisis

Operations performed in order to better visualize the data

  • Created new consolidated variables for LoanStatus
  • Created a single CreditScore variable
  • Renamed ProsperRating (Alpha) to ProsperRating, while keeping the alpha character AA-HR rating scheme
  • Renamed ListingCategory (numeric) to ListingCategory and changed all numeric values with category descriptions

# ProsperRating Proportions by LoanStatus_good - Facet bar

fig = plt.figure(figsize=[15,5])

# Derive bad_loan ticks
n_points_bad = bad_loans.shape[0]
max_count_bad = bad_loans['CombinedRating'].value_counts().max()
max_prop_bad = max_count_bad / n_points_bad

# Derive good_loan ticks
n_points_good = good_loans.shape[0]
max_count_good = good_loans['CombinedRating'].value_counts().max()
max_prop_good = max_count_good / n_points_good

max_prop = max(max_prop_good, max_prop_bad)

# generate tick mark locations and names
tick_props = np.arange(0, max_prop+0.02, 0.02)
tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in tick_props]

listing_order = ['AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'HR']

# create bad the plot

Unfavorable loans are most common in D and HR grade, while C grade dominates loans in good standing. Overall there is a higher proportion of good standing loans in higher grades. Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The correlation heatmap shows EstimatedReturn & BorrowerRate have a high positive correlation, and ProsperScore & BorrowerRate have a high negative correlation. When we pair them with LoanStatus however, we don't see a strong connection.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

As a consumer today, we often hear that credit score is of high importance when determining loan eligability but we did not see a clear relationship between unfavorable loan statuses and lower credit scores. One reason could be that the Credit Scores were all relatively high in the 600+ ranges. These typically indicate a "Good" credit rating and perhaps Prosper only accepts loan applicants with good credit.
